# Memory configuration for this project
#
# Copy this file to your project root as CLAUDE.md (or append to an existing one).
# Claude Code reads CLAUDE.md at startup and follows these instructions automatically.
# Replace LABEL_HERE with the project label you configured in ragconnect-web.

## Memory

This project uses RAGConnect for persistent memory.
Memory label: **`LABEL_HERE`**

### When to read from memory

Before answering any question about:
- architecture or design decisions
- past agreements or constraints
- the current state of a feature or component
- why something was done a particular way

Always call `memory_search` with `project_label="LABEL_HERE"` (derived from `memory-label`) before answering, even if
you think you already know. Memory may contain more recent information than your training.

### When to write to memory

Immediately after any of the following:
- a design or architectural decision is made
- an approach is agreed upon or rejected (and why)
- an important constraint or dependency is discovered
- a bug root cause is identified
- a non-obvious implementation detail is explained
- a task or milestone is completed

Use `memory_write` with `project_label="LABEL_HERE"`.
Write in third-person past tense, factually, without filler.

Good example:
> "Decided to use async LightRAG client because the sync version blocks the event loop
>  under concurrent MCP requests. Confirmed 2025-04-16."

Bad example:
> "We talked about making it async and that seems like a good idea."

### When to use local memory instead

Use `memory_search` / `memory_write` **without** a project_label (routes to local memory) for:
- personal notes that are not relevant to the team
- cross-project observations
- temporary scratch notes

### Routing reference

| Situation | project_label |
|-----------|--------------|
| Working in this project (`memory-label`) | `LABEL_HERE` |
| Personal / cross-project notes | *(omit)* |
